<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="26" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1040,2032]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,332,1426,1452]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Habitat:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zidarova &amp; Kopalová &amp; Vijver" authorityYear="2012" box="[333,616,1427,1452]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="sergiplaiana">
<emphasis box="[333,616,1427,1452]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Pinnularia sergiplaiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be found in several large lakes on the central plateau of Byers Peninsula near Limnopolar lake. The 
<typeStatus box="[629,682,1465,1491]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">type</typeStatus>
population was sampled from the sediment of a large lake, characterized by a weakly alkaline pH (7.4) and a low specific conductance (108 µS/cm). So far, the species has been rarely found on Hurd Peninsula where from it was previously reported as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Krammer 2000: 61) Kulikovskiy, Lange-Bert. &amp; Metzeltin (2010: 359)" authorityName="Kulikovskiy, Lange-Bert. &amp; Metzeltin" authorityPageNumber="359" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Krammer" baseAuthorityPageNumber="61" baseAuthorityYear="2000" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="media">
<emphasis box="[1131,1231,1543,1568]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">P. media</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K." pageId="15" pageNumber="26" refId="ref15524" refString="Krammer, K. (2000) The genus Pinnularia. In: H. Lange-Bertalot (ed.), Diatoms of Europe, Diatoms of the European Inland waters and comparable habitats. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag K. G., 1: 703 pp." type="book" year="2000">Krammer 2000: 61</bibRefCitation>
) Kulikovskiy, Lange-Bert. &amp; Metzeltin (2010: 359)
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zidarova, R." box="[805,981,1581,1607]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" pagination="19 - 35" refId="ref17905" refString="Zidarova, R. (2008) Algae from Livingston Island (S Shetland Islands): a checklist. Phytologica Balcanic a 14: 19 - 35." type="journal article" year="2008">Zidarova 2008</bibRefCitation>
, p. 30, fig. 24).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="26" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1040,2032]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,343,1619,1645]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Etymology:</emphasis>
–The species is named in honor of our colleague Sergi Pla (
<collectingRegion box="[1045,1136,1620,1646]" country="Spain" name="Madrid" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Madrid</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1148,1219,1620,1646]" name="Spain" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Spain</collectingCountry>
), in recognition of his contribution to the knowledge of Antarctic algae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1040,2032]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,403,1696,1722]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Observations:—</emphasis>
This new species clearly belongs to the complex of taxa around 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Smith" authorityYear="1853" box="[1172,1315,1697,1722]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="divergens">
<emphasis box="[1172,1315,1697,1722]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">P. divergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on the presence of the typical rounded thickenings in the central area and the lateral annexes to the proximal raphe pores. Most of the species and varieties belonging to this complex are usually larger (
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K." box="[1237,1424,1774,1800]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" refId="ref15524" refString="Krammer, K. (2000) The genus Pinnularia. In: H. Lange-Bertalot (ed.), Diatoms of Europe, Diatoms of the European Inland waters and comparable habitats. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag K. G., 1: 703 pp." type="book" year="2000">Krammer 2000</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="W. Smith" authorityYear="1853" box="[151,402,1813,1838]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="divergens">
<emphasis box="[151,402,1813,1838]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Pinnularia divergens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a valve width of 
<quantity box="[660,783,1813,1839]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="16.5" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="14.0">14–19 µm</quantity>
(vs. 
<quantity box="[843,966,1813,1839]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.3" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" unit="mm" value="11.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="10.0">10–13 µm</quantity>
) and has clearly capitate to subcapitate apices. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kulikovskiy, Lange-Bert. &amp; Metzeltin" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Krammer" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[238,443,1852,1877]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="media">
<emphasis box="[238,443,1852,1877]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Pinnularia media</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has similar valve dimensions but is characterized by clearly capitate apices and lacks the typical fascia. 
<taxonomicName authority="Zidarova &amp; Kopalová &amp; Vijver, 2012" authorityName="Zidarova &amp; Kopalová &amp; Vijver" authorityYear="2012" box="[368,679,1891,1916]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="livingstonensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[368,679,1891,1916]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Pinnularia livingstonensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[688,780,1891,1917]" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(see below) can be distinguished by its typical parallel margins and its broadly rounded apices. 
<taxonomicName box="[631,854,1929,1954]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="crozetii">
<emphasis box="[631,854,1929,1954]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Pinnularia crozetii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks the rounded thickenings in the central area and has a more lanceolate valve outline. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kutz. 1844: 93) Rabenh. (1864: 222)" authorityName="Rabenh." authorityPageNumber="222" authorityYear="1864" baseAuthorityName="Kutz." baseAuthorityPageNumber="93" baseAuthorityYear="1844" box="[624,1390,1968,1994]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Pinnularia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="15" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="divergentissima">
<emphasis box="[624,942,1968,1993]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="26">Pinnularia divergentissima</emphasis>
(Kütz.1844: 93) Rabenh. (1864: 222)
</taxonomicName>
has a somewhat similar valve outline but lacks the central thickenings.
</paragraph>
